<p class="pageheader">Alan Crosby Q&A
<hr noshade/></p>
<b>07-11-2004</b> - 
<B>EQ Vault:</B> Well Alan, you're taking over for another Alan. Can you give us a little introduction and tell us how you came to your current role as the Community Manager for EverQuest? 
<P>
<B>Alan Crosby:</B> Well I was hand selected by Gnomes due to my short size and jolly demeanor. Hehe ... Actually, once Absor decided to move on, I applied for the position internally. After an extensive set of interviews and some torture, I was selected. 
<P>
<B>EQ Vault:</B> Absor's shoes are a touch big, what do you hope to do to fill them? 
<P>
<B>Alan Crosby:</B> Absor does have huge feet. I believe he wears Clown Shoes. I plan on using newspaper to fill in all of the extra room.
<P>
<B>EQ Vault:</B> Will you be doing anything different that the community should expect? 
<P>
<B>Alan Crosby:</B> I have all kinds of fun stuff in store for you folks. Wait and see! 
<P>
<B>EQ Vault:</B> For those not familiar with the life of a Community Manager, can you run us through a day in the life of the new CM? 
<P>
<B>Alan Crosby:</B> Most of my day is spent in email and on the boards. Often I am seen scurrying about to get approval or facts for posts and interviews. This is truly grueling, mind-wracking stuff. At the end of the day I retire to my office to ponder life and the meaning of "Nerf".
<P>
<B>EQ Vault:</B> Many gamers dream of holding your job. What kind of qualifications does it take, and what would you suggest to the thousands of folks gunning for a spot like your own? 
<P>
<B>Alan Crosby:</B> It takes really tough skin, in fact, they tested my skin with several needles during the selection process to see how much poking and prodding I could take. After 4 years of doing CS for EverQuest, my skin was pretty darn thick. 
<P>
I would suggest that anyone wishing to be a Community Manager be an active part of the game community. Make sure you are rational and positive and you may get noticed, much like that Moorgard guy over on EQ2. The important thing to remember is to be a positive force in the community. That is not to say that you cannot disagree with decisions a game has made, rather that you explain yourself clearly and intelligently without name calling or vulgarity. 
<P>
<B>EQ Vault:</B> Community Managers are famous for hanging out all over the net, such as EQII's Moorgard, do you plan to follow his example? If so, where can fans expect to find you lurking? 
<P>
<B>Alan Crosby:</B> I plan to spend as much time as I can on the internet posting on Community Sites and doing a better job than Moorgard. That's right Moorgard I am calling you out! You and me after school behind the gym. Bring a lunch!
<P>
<B>EQ Vault:</B> Personally, which classes do you currently play and enjoy? Why? 
<P>
<B>Alan Crosby:</B> Now, now, I am not falling for this trap! I have played every class at one time or another. I have likes and dislikes for all of them, however I am especially fond of anything that Halflings can be. (How is that for a PC answer?) 
<P>
<B>EQ Vault:</B> Thank you for taking the time to sit down and be grilled. Is there anything you would like to add? 
<P>
<B>Alan Crosby:</B> I look forward to being a proactive, positive part of the community. We have a lot of things planned to bring all of you back into the EQ community and you will see those grow to fruition in the coming weeks and months.
<P>
Thanks for your time folks and thanks for being a part of Norrath. 

